I"Ÿ<p>Assuming cognition is the result of a <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/premotor-theory-of-attention-is-fundamentally-enactive">tight sensorimotor loop</a> between the <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/perception-is-context-dependent">percepts</a> and <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/phenomenal-space-is-adaptive">actions</a> of an individual, evolution suggests that the loop still provides <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/representationism-in-cognition-is-adaptationism-in-evolution">an optimal grip on the world through adaptation</a> to ecology. In this way, Darwinism casts enaction in a light of sophisticated realism. However, enaction responds that the plethora of observed adaptations (e.g. various numbers of photoreceptor types), indicates <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/world-image-is-a-chicken-egg-problem">a disconnect between world and images</a>.</p>
